Q1 A

In this part we are asked to establish a fraction plot consists of 1 to 10 dimensional 1000 sample data, and their eculedian distances to all data.

#dimension_1
nof_samples=1000
data_points1=runif(nof_samples,-1,1)
data_points1=matrix(data_points1,ncol=1)
euclidean_distance1=sqrt((data_points1[ ,1]-0)^2)
x1=euclidean_distance1<1
r1=sum(x1)

#dimension_2

As a result we obtained the higher gets the dimension the lower gets the fraction, meaning that as the higher we go in dimension the curse of dimensionalty welcomes us as the fraction of hypershere to hypercube gets down to lower numbers. This is because as the dimensions increase the distance between the points in n dimensional space get further from each other with a higher probability.

Q1 B

In this part we did the same procedure as the pi estimation in the class and the dimensional fraction as in the first part. We did for 2d and 3d. The corresonding pi estimation and fraciton in the scattered plot

#2D
nof_samples=1000
data_points=runif(nof_samples*2,-1,1)
data_points=matrix(data_points,ncol=2)
plot(data_points)
euclidean_distance=sqrt((data_points[ ,1]-0)^2 + (data_points[ ,2]-0)^2)
is_in_circle=euclidean_distance<=1
nof_sphere=sum(is_in_circle)
estimated_pi=(nof_sphere/nof_samples)*6
print(estimated_pi)
## [1] 4.824
print(pi)
## [1] 3.141593
points(data_points,col=as.numeric(is_in_circle)+1)

#3D
library(scatterplot3d)
nof_samples=1000
data_points=runif(nof_samples*3,-1,1)
data_points=matrix(data_points,ncol=3)
euclidean_distance=sqrt((data_points[ ,1]-0)^2 + (data_points[ ,2]-0)^2+(data_points[ ,3]-0)^2)
is_in_1=euclidean_distance<=1
sphere=sum(is_in_1)
estimated_pi=sphere/nof_samples*6
print(estimated_pi)
## [1] 3.078
print(pi)
## [1] 3.141593
scatterplot3d(data_points,color=as.numeric(is_in_1)+1)

For each dimension is uniformly randomly distributed between -1 and +1 we used Rnorm function for the 100 sample with runif function for the first 1000 examples.

However, since the main purpose of the study is to determine main factors that impacts the value of the house, we also wanted to look at what the parameters actually mean one by one. This is where we have seen that there are some parameters that are not necessary linked or very loosely linked with the value of an house. For instance, feature AGE defined as: proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940, whereas, MEDV defined as Median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000’s. We could not see how these features impacts the value of the houses, therefore, decided to not to use them.

In the summary, we have seen that comp.1 is explaining the variance the best solely in 1 dimension. Therefore we dived deeper into how the data explained with this comp.

When we look at the summary, we see that Comp.1 takes all features into account except chas feature. On the other hand, when we examined the bor plot, we have seen that there are some clear distinct groups. For instance, while obsveravations between 180-350 (say its Group 1) seems to have an weight on negative coefficients more, whereas houses between 350 to 500 (say its Group 2), have weight on positive coefficients. From here, we can make some infurances such as Group 1 houses are in the residential areas, have high number of rooms, far away from the employement centers, and black population is higher. With the same logic, we can make inferences for the Group 2 as well by focusing on the positive coefficients.

#taking transpose for the sampling purposes
transposed_nd=transpose(netflixdata)

samp_tran_nd=sample(transposed_nd,1000)

#reversing it back
samp_nd=transpose(samp_tran_nd)

#imputating the NA with kNNImputation method
knn.nd=knnImputation(samp_nd,k=10)

We have been provided by two data sets, one of which was related to titles of the movies, the other one was respective ratings by the observers. In order to initiate our study, we needed to combine these two. Since it was relatively much easier to do in Excel, we prefered to complete it there. However, since the hardware requirement in the following activities are quite high, we sampled the 1000 observations randomly and for this purpose we first transposed the data and then reversed it back after sampling. From here, we moved on to impute the missing values. For this, we used k nearest neighbour imputation method we found as a quite reasonable method. kNN determines the missing value by looking out the people who have similar ratings in other movies with the people has not given rating and fills the value by making calculation on those peoples ratings for the target missing value.

#creating the distance matrix
f = distanceMatrix(knn.nd,'euclid')

#preparing distance function for clasical multidimensional scaling
mat_knn_nd=as.matrix(f)
#executing classical multidimensional scaling
mds_netflix=cmdscale(mat_knn_nd)

#dividing unnecessary numbers
mds_nd_div=mds_netflix/10000000

#ploting the result
plot(mds_nd_div)
text(mds_nd_div, names(knn.nd))

In order to perform classical multidimensional scaling, we need to calculate distances between observations first. Then, we should also provide it in matrix format.
